## Web Search Results

**SQ4 — Does Semgrep AI already produce fire-on-bad/silent-on-good corpus pairs and integrate as a Claude Code skill?**

- Semgrep Assistant's custom-rule-generation feature takes three **user-supplied** inputs: a rule description, an example of bad code, and an example of good code — the corpus pairs are *not* auto-derived from a found bug or fix diff (https://semgrep.dev/blog/2024/the-tech-behind-semgrep-assistant/, also confirmed in https://semgrep.dev/blog/2023/using-ai-to-write-secure-code-with-semgrep/).
- Semgrep Assistant **does** run a fire-on-bad / silent-on-good verification gate internally: the generation loop raises `AiNonFatalResponseParseError` when "Rule matched the good code that it should not have matched against," and retries (https://semgrep.dev/blog/2024/the-tech-behind-semgrep-assistant/).
- Semgrep's own self-reported quality bar: rules generated correctly are "around a 3 out of 10 on a complexity scale" (https://semgrep.dev/blog/2023/using-ai-to-write-secure-code-with-semgrep/).
- Distribution: Semgrep Assistant runs inside the Semgrep Cloud Platform / GitHub-PR flow. No mention of Claude Code skill integration, MCP exposure of rule-gen, or callability outside Semgrep's own UI in the source pages (https://semgrep.dev/products/semgrep-code/assistant/, https://semgrep.dev/docs/semgrep-assistant/overview).
- **Gap-to-wedge**: Semgrep AI's input contract is `(description, 1 bad, 1 good) → 1 rule`; `/slo-rulegen`'s wedge contract is `(bug_summary, fix_diff, file_paths) → N variation rules + auto-generated corpus pairs`, callable inside a Claude Code session. Verification of the rule itself is not the differentiator; corpus auto-derivation, variation enumeration, and in-session callability are.

**SQ6 — Do Clippy's `unwrap_used` / `indexing_slicing` / `arithmetic_side_effects` cover ≥60% of CWE-248 / CWE-190 sink shapes?**

- All three lints exist and are in the **`restriction` group with default level `Allow`** — i.e. users must explicitly opt in via `#![warn(clippy::indexing_slicing)]` or equivalent (https://rust-lang.github.io/rust-clippy/master/index.html, https://github.com/rust-lang/rust-clippy/blob/master/clippy_lints/src/indexing_slicing.rs).
- `clippy::indexing_slicing` source comment: "Checks for usage of indexing or slicing that may panic at runtime… To avoid implicit panics from indexing and slicing" — explicitly the CWE-248 panic-DoS sink shape (https://github.com/rust-lang/rust-clippy/blob/master/clippy_lints/src/indexing_slicing.rs).
- `clippy::arithmetic_side_effects` covers `+`, `-`, `*`, `<<` overflow per the Rust Reference, plus `/`, `%` panic-on-divide-by-zero — the CWE-190/CWE-191 sink shape (https://rust-lang.github.io/rust-clippy/master/index.html).
- The arxiv study "Unleashing the Power of Clippy in Real-World Rust Projects" finds `arithmetic_side_effects` is among the highest-frequency warnings in real projects AND that "the warning patterns under the arithmetic_side_effects category pose a considerable challenge for automatic fixing by Clippy" (https://arxiv.org/pdf/2310.11738).
- Clippy attaches **no CWE IDs** to its lints — the CWE mapping has to be added by `/slo-rulegen`. Issue #6636 ("forbid all expect and unwrap use") shows the lint exists and is debated for production opt-in (https://github.com/rust-lang/rust-clippy/issues/6636).
- **Implication for the integration question**: at the *sink-shape* level, Clippy's three restriction lints do cover the CWE-248 / CWE-190 surface broadly, but they fire on every occurrence with no taint, no source/sink reasoning, no per-handler context (e.g. "indexed by request body length"), and no CWE tag. The web evidence supports composition (consume Clippy's output as a coarse fence, layer Semgrep taint-mode rules on top) rather than replacement. No source claims a quantified ≥60% sink-shape overlap; that number would have to be measured against a corpus, not asserted from documentation.

**SQ9 — Publication-risk default for vulnerable corpus snippets: gitignored vs tracked?**

- The official `semgrep/semgrep-rules` repo is fully public on GitHub with 3,966+ commits across language directories — vulnerable snippets are committed, not gitignored (https://github.com/semgrep/semgrep-rules).
- Contributing guide mandates a paired test file with the **same basename** as the rule yaml: e.g. `my-rule.yaml` + `my-rule.js`. Inside the test file, deliberately-vulnerable lines are tagged with `// ruleid: my-rule` (fire-on-bad expectation) and safe lines with `// ok: my-rule` (silent-on-good). Quote: "In the test file, include examples that mark: What is expected to be a finding. What is not a finding." (https://semgrep.dev/docs/contributing/contributing-to-semgrep-rules-repository).
- Trail of Bits' public semgrep-rules pack follows the same public-tracked convention (https://github.com/trailofbits/semgrep-rules).
- 0xdea's pack documents the strongest version of the precedent: "Each rule is accompanied by an actual vulnerable source code that was targeted by an exploit, with vulnerable lines marked with `// ruleid: ...`" — and is also public on GitHub (https://github.com/0xdea/semgrep-rules).
- Searches surfaced **no GitHub Acceptable-Use takedown notices** against semgrep-rules-style repos for the deliberately-vulnerable test-snippet content. The convention surfaced everywhere is inline annotation (`// ruleid:` / `// ok:`), not segregated bad/good directories.
- **Implication for the default**: precedent across the Semgrep ecosystem (Semgrep Inc, Trail of Bits, 0xdea, elttam, CodeVigilant, Decurity) is *tracked-but-labelled-with-`// ruleid:`*. The compliance-fine framing in the idea doc is not corroborated by any takedown evidence in these searches.

