## Web Search Results

### SQ7 — Corpus layout convention (Semgrep rule + test co-location)

- Semgrep's official testing docs require **co-located** test files: a rule at `path/to/rule.yaml` looks for siblings `path/to/rule.<lang-ext>` (e.g. `rule.py`, `rule.rs`) — not a separate `tests/` tree. Source: [Test rules | Semgrep](https://semgrep.dev/docs/writing-rules/testing-rules).
- The test filename **must match the rule filename**, only the extension differs; this is the dominant convention used in the upstream `semgrep/semgrep-rules` repo. Source: [Test rules | Semgrep](https://semgrep.dev/docs/writing-rules/testing-rules), [semgrep/semgrep-rules](https://github.com/semgrep/semgrep-rules).
- A `.test.yaml` extension is reserved for the case where the **rule's target language is YAML itself** (avoids ambiguity with the rule's own `.yaml` file). Not relevant for Rust corpora. Source: [Test rules | Semgrep](https://semgrep.dev/docs/writing-rules/testing-rules), [Issue #1228 — Invalid schema on yaml/* unit test files](https://github.com/semgrep/semgrep-rules/issues/1228).
- Annotation convention: `// ruleid: <id>` on the line above bad code, `// ok: <id>` for negative cases — used inline in the test file rather than as separate `bad.rs` / `good.rs` files. Source: [Test rules | Semgrep](https://semgrep.dev/docs/writing-rules/testing-rules), [Contribute rules to the Semgrep Registry](https://semgrep.dev/docs/contributing/contributing-to-semgrep-rules-repository).
- Issue #2799 confirms `semgrep --test` is the canonical runner that consumes this layout. Source: [`semgrep --test` a yaml file · Issue #2799](https://github.com/returntocorp/semgrep/issues/2799).

### SQ8 — CI + local wiring (pre-commit vs lefthook vs prek)

- Semgrep ships a **first-party pre-commit hooks repo** (`semgrep/pre-commit`), so `pre-commit` remains the path-of-least-resistance default in 2026. Source: [semgrep/pre-commit](https://github.com/semgrep/pre-commit), [Customize Semgrep in pre-commit | Semgrep](https://semgrep.dev/docs/kb/integrations/customize-semgrep-precommit).
- **Lefthook** (Go, 2019) is positioned as faster and parallel-by-default but does **not** auto-install tools or pull remote hook configs — you must wire each invocation yourself. Source: [Git hooks management with pre-commit and lefthook | 0xDC.me](https://0xdc.me/blog/git-hooks-management-with-pre-commit-and-lefthook/), [dotdc/test-lefthook-and-pre-commit](https://github.com/dotdc/test-lefthook-and-pre-commit).
- A **Rust-native equivalent has emerged**: `prek` (j178/prek) — a drop-in `pre-commit` replacement written in Rust, compatible with existing `.pre-commit-config.yaml`, no Python dependency. Discussed on HN in late 2025/early 2026. Source: [j178/prek](https://github.com/j178/prek), [prek docs](https://prek.j178.dev/), [HN: Better pre-commit, re-engineered in Rust](https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=45931273), [HN: Prek: A better, faster, drop-in pre-commit replacement](https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=46873138).
- Implication for a `cargo`-shaped repo: `pre-commit-config.yaml` is still the canonical config format; `prek` reads it without changes, so a project can adopt the Rust runner without rewriting CI. No `cargo-semgrep` subcommand wrapper surfaced in results.

### SQ3 — Web-class CWE inclusion in a Rust top-10

- Searches for axum/sqlx-specific SQLi / XSS / SSRF CVEs in 2024–2025 returned **no major framework-level advisories** in those classes. The hits were either stdlib or transport-layer issues, not webapp injection. Source: [RustSec Advisories index](https://rustsec.org/advisories/), [CVE-2024-24576 — std::process::Command on Windows (BatBadBut)](https://blog.rust-lang.org/2024/04/09/cve-2024-24576.html), [CVE-2024-43402 — std::process::Command Windows hardening](https://blog.rust-lang.org/2024/09/04/cve-2024-43402.html).
- One indirect hit relevant to a Rust web stack: **RUSTSEC-2024-0421** affects `idna < 1.0.0` (used transitively by `url`, then by `sqlx ≤ 0.8.2`, `reqwest ≤ 0.12.8`) — a Punycode/IDNA confusion that maps to **CWE-20 / CWE-1007** (homograph), enabling phishing/SSRF-adjacent URL spoofing rather than classic SQLi or stored XSS. Source: [OSV — RUSTSEC-2024-0421](https://osv.dev/vulnerability/RUSTSEC-2024-0421).
- **RUSTSEC-2025-0028** surfaced in the Wiz vulnerability DB (referenced as a 2025 advisory). Source: [RUSTSEC-2025-0028 | Wiz](https://www.wiz.io/vulnerability-database/cve/rustsec-2025-0028).
- Aggregate Rust-lang CVE listings remain dominated by stdlib/runtime issues and `unsafe`/FFI memory bugs, not the OWASP Top-10 web classes. Source: [Rust-lang CVEs | cvedetails.com](https://www.cvedetails.com/vulnerability-list/vendor_id-19029/product_id-48677/Rust-lang-Rust.html), [MITRE CVE keyword=rust](https://cve.mitre.org/cgi-bin/cvekey.cgi?keyword=rust).
- **Search verdict:** these three queries did not produce evidence that CWE-89 / CWE-79 / CWE-918 belong in a frequency-ranked Rust top-10 based on RustSec/OSV advisories. They may still warrant inclusion on a *threat-class* basis (axum apps absolutely can be vulnerable when devs hand-roll SQL or HTML), but the public advisory corpus does not back a frequency claim. A targeted RustSec-DB CWE tally (SQ1's main task) is needed to settle this.

