## Web Search Results

### Q1 — CWE susceptibility ranking for Rust

- The **2025 CWE Top 25** (published by MITRE/CISA on 2025-12-11) is the authoritative cross-language baseline for the topical period; the current top entries are CWE-79 (XSS), CWE-787 (out-of-bounds write), CWE-89 (SQLi), CWE-352 (CSRF), and CWE-22 (path traversal). Source: https://cwe.mitre.org/top25/archive/2025/2025_cwe_top25.html and https://www.cisa.gov/news-events/alerts/2025/12/11/2025-cwe-top-25-most-dangerous-software-weaknesses
- A **2026 academic dataset (RustXec)** that mined RustSec found Rust-specific CVE distributions skewed to: memory-corruption (31 cases) and denial-of-service (28 cases), with the most frequent CWEs being **CWE-787 (out-of-bounds write, 9 cases), CWE-415 (double free, 8 cases), and CWE-400 (uncontrolled resource consumption, 7 cases)** — directly relevant to confirming the user's prior expectation that panic-DoS and unsafe-FFI classes dominate. Source: https://people.cs.vt.edu/xinw/publications/RustXec26-B38KjKAe.pdf
- Recent RustSec advisories continue to feature panic-on-malformed-input, unsoundness, plaintext exposure in decryption, permission bypass, and shell expansion — confirming the wedge's "panic-DoS + injection" framing. Source: https://rustsec.org/advisories/ and https://github.com/rustsec/advisory-db
- A separate KEV-aligned CWE Top 10 was also published in 2025, useful for weighting "actually exploited in the wild" vs. theoretical risk. Source: https://cwe.mitre.org/top25/archive/2025/2025_kev_insights.html

### Q2 — Direct competitors in AI-driven SAST rule generation

- **Semgrep Assistant (2026)**: AI-driven, but focused on **finding triage** (claims 96% alignment with human triage) and a "Memories" feature that learns from past triage decisions — *not* a per-bug rule synthesiser. Custom rules are still authored by humans in YAML against a community registry of 3,000+ rules. Source: https://semgrep.dev/blog/2026/semgrep-supply-chain-extends-reachability-coverage-to-rust/ and https://corgea.com/blog/compare/snyk-vs-semgrep/
- **Snyk Code / DeepCode AI**: AI engine handles both detection and **auto-fix suggestions in IDE/PR**. Custom rules exist but are **Enterprise-only Early Access**, written in a proprietary Datalog-based query language against Snyk's internal "event graph" — opaque, not human-editable in the Semgrep sense. Source: https://appsecsanta.com/snyk-code and https://konvu.com/compare/snyk-vs-semgrep
- **Pricing baseline (2026)**: Semgrep Code $30/contributor/mo; Snyk advanced SAST starts ~$50/mo per developer with custom rules gated behind Enterprise contact-sales. Source: https://dev.to/rahulxsingh/semgrep-pricing-in-2026-open-source-vs-team-vs-enterprise-costs-3dic and https://dev.to/rahulxsingh/snyk-vs-semgrep-sca-platform-vs-custom-sast-rules-in-2026-3047
- **Gap confirmed**: none of the surveyed 2026 tools advertise a workflow that takes `(bug_summary, fix_diff, file_paths)` and emits Rust-idiomatic Semgrep rules with a fire/silent verification gate; they do AI-triage or AI-autofix, not AI-rule-synthesis. Source comparison set: https://appsecsanta.com/sast-tools/semgrep-vs-snyk-code, https://www.aikido.dev/blog/snyk-vs-semgrep, https://vibe-eval.com/testing/sast-tools-ai-code, https://sanj.dev/post/ai-code-security-tools-comparison, https://deepsource.com/resources/snyk-alternatives

### Q4 — Semgrep Rust frontend reality in 2026

- Rust support began as **beta in Feb 2023** and has been progressively hardened. By 2026 Semgrep is using Rust taint mode in its own **Supply Chain reachability analysis** product (e.g. `bcder` advisory analysis), so taint mode with `pattern-either` source/sink declarations works on real Rust code. Source: https://semgrep.dev/blog/2026/semgrep-supply-chain-extends-reachability-coverage-to-rust/ and https://semgrep.dev/docs/supported-languages
- Rust-specific taint improvements documented: parameter-with-pattern-matching propagates taint (including nested patterns), and **macro calls can taint through their arguments** — important for axum/tokio/`tracing::instrument` macro-heavy code. Source: https://semgrep.dev/docs/writing-rules/data-flow/taint-mode/overview and https://semgrep.dev/docs/writing-rules/data-flow/taint-mode/advanced
- `pattern-either` semantics are documented as identical across languages (it is a list combinator inside `pattern-sources` / `pattern-sinks` / `pattern-sanitizers`). Source: https://semgrep.dev/docs/writing-rules/data-flow/taint-mode/
- Web search did not surface authoritative 2026 docs on (a) `pattern-inside unsafe { ... }` block selection, (b) metavariable type filtering across Rust trait bounds, or (c) macro-FP rate benchmarks — flagged as **inconclusive** for this slice; a synthesis pass should run targeted fetches against the semgrep-rules GitHub repo and the semgrep/semgrep issue tracker `[lang/rust]` filter.

